In a nutshell, though: a subnet can be set up by a subnet owner to achieve a certain goal that's done via ML: text-generation, image-generation, etc.  The miners receive queries related to that task from the validators, and have to respond.  There is a reward module in the validator that assesses the responses and then ranks the miners according to its standards.  The validators have their own consensus process (so that any validator that's too far out from the overall majority consensus loses something called "vtrust" and faces deregistration).  The network's emissions are portioned out to the subnets based on the root network of validators (they have their own consensus for weighting the subnets -- weights are currently manually set by the operators of the root network validators), and a subnet's share of the emissions are apportioned out (after the 18% cut for the subnet owner is removed): 50% goes to the validators and is distributed according to validator stake and vtrust, and 50% goes to miners and is distributed according to rank.

The time for **v2.0** has finally come. We just merged the streaming branch into main - we are live! 
https://github.com/opentensor/prompting/releases/tag/v2.0.0

**SN1 is now a fully streaming-based subnet.**

While it took a while, I believe that this was one of the most thorough and most carefully planned upgrades that has been done by any subnet in Bittensor. We  created a dedicated test subnet, produced extensive documentation and resources, ran tracked experiments around the clock for 3 weeks (at significant expense!), analyzed the network daily, provided no less than 3 validators and 3 miners to support data acquisition and debugging activities on netuid 102. Huge thanks to the killer team working behind the scenes on this. Seriously, take a bow @ferpe  and @brian | macrocosmos.

## What does this mean?

This means that there is a new synapse object that the validators and miners are passing back and forth, called `StreamPromptingSynapse`. This object enables the miners to submit their responses in small chunks (aka streaming) so that they are less exposed to the risk of getting zero rewards for timing out. This means that miners can focus on quality, rather than the clock. We are also going to release a time-based penalty in the near future so that speed becomes a more explicit competitive axis.

Our frontend is almost ready, and with a streaming backend one of the final pieces has fallen into place. 

## What happens now?

- All of the miners must update and use `StreamPromptingSynapse` instead of `PromptingSynapse`. See the docs for more details.
- All of the validators must promptly(!!) update to v2.0.
- Registrations will be disabled for 24 hours while we monitor the transition. 
- We will be stopping our 102 experiment today.
- Tomorrow I will be setting the version to 2.0 on weight setting validators.
